          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">This isn't particularly useful.\nThe edges are over-populated on the visualization.\nIf there were structure in the graph that were interesting,\nwe'd find it hard to elucidate.\nHere, we can rely on the principle of small multiples\nto design a more effective visualizations.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "RGSE",
      "code_hash": "dc942cca48062f2d938e7a9c8aeb483d",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h2 id=\"nxviz-faceting-api\"><code>nxviz</code> faceting API</h2>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Graph visualization panels are the solution here.\nWe use categorical metadata on nodes or edges\nto facet our visualizations.\n(Faceting refers to creating subplots that contain a subset of the full dataset,\nso that one can optimize for visual clarity.)</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Because nodes are more easily arranged than edges,\nwe can facet our graph out by edge categories into <strong>panels</strong>.\nAs such, one subcategory of graph visualization panels\nis defined by a faceting of our graph by edge categories.\nHere are some examples.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
